{
  "llm": {
    "provider": "ollama",
    "config": {
      "ollama_base_url": "http://host.docker.internal:11434",
      "api_key": "dummy_key", 
      "temperature": 0,
      "model": "llama3.1:latest",
      "max_tokens": 8148
    }
  },
  "embedder": {
    "provider": "ollama",
    "config": {
      "ollama_base_url": "http://host.docker.internal:11434",
      "model": "embeddinggemma",
      "embedding_dims": 768
    }
  },
  "vector_store": {
    "provider": "qdrant",
    "config": {
      "host": "qdrant-mem0",
      "port": 6333,
      "collection_name": "mem0-working",
      "embedding_model_dims": 768,
      "on_disk": true,
      "indexed_fields": [
        "concern",
        "category",
        "user_id",
        "customer_id",
        "project_id"
      ]
    }
  },
  "graph_store": {
    "provider": "neo4j",
    "config": {
      "url": "bolt://mem0-neo4j:7687",
      "username": "neo4j",
      "password": "neo4mem0",
      "database": "neo4j"
    },
    "llm": {
      "provider": "ollama",
      "config": {
        "ollama_base_url": "http://host.docker.internal:11434",
        "model": "llama3.1:latest",
        "temperature": 0,
        "max_tokens": 8148
      }
    },
    "custom_prompt": "Extract only analytically useful entities and relationships from source content.\n\nPrioritize entities such as:\n- person, company, organization, institution, regulator, community\n- market, sector, domain, product, service, tool, platform, framework, language, standard, regulation, method, feature\n- geography, segment, customer group, use case, environment, risk category\n- metric, benchmark, price, cost, rate, percentage, volume, performance indicator, version, date, period, event\n\nPrioritize relationships such as:\n- operates_in\n- regulates\n- publishes\n- announces\n- launches\n- develops\n- uses\n- depends_on\n- integrates_with\n- replaces\n- competes_with\n- partners_with\n- acquires\n- affects\n- causes\n- enables\n- limits\n- improves\n- worsens\n- compared_with\n- adopted_by\n- cited_by\n- forecast_for\n\nIgnore weak, generic, or conversational entities.\nPrefer entities and relationships that improve analytical retrieval and synthesis."
  },
  "enable_graph": true,
  "custom_instructions": "Your Task: Extract and store high-value analytical knowledge from verified articles, reports, interviews, expert commentary, technical documents, and web sources so a downstream analyst agent can produce strong synthesis, comparison, and reporting outputs.\n\nInformation to Extract:\n\n1. Source and provenance:\n- Title\n- Publisher, organization, institution, or media outlet\n- Author or speaker if available\n- Publication date\n- URL or source identifier if available\n- Document type if inferable: article, report, interview, announcement, technical note, opinion piece, benchmark, regulation, blog post, documentation, white paper\n\n2. Core subject matter:\n- Main topic, domain, market, technology, product, method, regulation, or issue discussed\n- Scope of analysis: geography, industry, company, platform, language, standard, product line, business function, technical capability, time period\n- Key themes, subtopics, and problem areas\n\n3. Observed facts:\n- Concrete statements presented as factual by the source\n- Quantitative data: counts, rates, percentages, prices, costs, volumes, performance metrics, adoption figures, incidents, capacity, rankings, benchmarks\n- Qualitative but material facts: launches, deprecations, policy changes, technical changes, organizational decisions, market moves, feature releases, partnerships, acquisitions, legal decisions\n- Comparisons across time, competitors, products, technologies, regions, customer segments, architectures, or methods\n\n4. Actors, entities, and objects:\n- Companies, institutions, regulators, standards bodies, experts, teams, communities, vendors, competitors\n- Products, services, tools, platforms, frameworks, languages, datasets, regulations, methodologies, components, features\n- User groups, customer segments, professions, environments, use cases, risk categories\n\n5. Relationships and structure:\n- Who does what, uses what, builds what, regulates what, depends on what, competes with what, replaces what, integrates with what\n- Supply, dependency, interoperability, causality, ownership, partnership, acquisition, influence, compliance, compatibility, migration, comparison\n\n6. Explanations and implications:\n- Explicit causes, drivers, constraints, risks, tradeoffs, bottlenecks, opportunities, strategic motives, technical reasons, business consequences\n- Stated implications for users, customers, companies, engineers, operators, regulators, markets, or ecosystems\n\n7. Opinions and interpretations:\n- Attributed expert views, judgments, commentary, analysis, concerns, recommendations, critiques, and interpretations\n- Positions expressed by named or attributable actors\n- Reasoning offered to explain trends, choices, or consequences\n\n8. Projections and forward-looking statements:\n- Forecasts, scenarios, expectations, guidance, roadmaps, anticipated changes, warnings, timelines, future bets\n- Claims about likely evolution, adoption, disruption, competition, performance, regulation, architecture, or demand\n\n9. Temporal context and uncertainty:\n- Dates, periods, sequence of events, before/after comparisons, effective dates, deadlines, release windows, forecast horizons\n- Whether a statement is a fact, opinion, estimate, forecast, rumor, or hypothesis\n- Degree of uncertainty if explicitly stated\n\nGuidelines:\n- Store memories as dense, self-contained, source-grounded analytical units.\n- Prefer many atomic memories over one broad summary.\n- Preserve exact names, dates, figures, units, currencies, percentages, versions, standards, and baselines.\n- Clearly distinguish:\n  - FACT\n  - OPINION\n  - PROJECTION\n- Keep contradictions if they come from different sources or actors.\n- Include enough context in each memory so it remains understandable when retrieved alone.\n- Preserve attribution whenever a claim is made by a person, company, institution, regulator, expert, or source.\n- Preserve causal links, comparisons, and dependencies because they are highly valuable for analysis.\n- Prioritize recall over compression, as long as the memory remains specific and useful.\n- Normalize wording for retrieval quality, but do not remove meaningful nuance.\n\nExclude:\n- Generic introductions and filler\n- SEO text, navigation text, cookie banners, newsletter prompts, social prompts\n- Purely stylistic phrasing with no analytical value\n- Repetition with no additional information\n- Personal preference memories, assistant behavior, or conversational metadata\n- Claims too vague to be analytically useful without context",
  "custom_fact_extraction_prompt": "You extract analytically useful memories from the conversation for downstream retrieval.\n\nYou may use information from both user and assistant messages. Ignore system messages.\n\nReturn only valid JSON.\nDo not return markdown.\nDo not return code fences.\nDo not return explanations.\nDo not return any keys other than \"facts\".\n\nRequired output format:\n{\"facts\": [\"...\"]}\n\nIf nothing useful is found, return exactly:\n{\"facts\": []}\n\nHard requirements:\n- The top-level value must be a JSON object.\n- The object must contain a single key named \"facts\".\n- The value of \"facts\" must be a JSON array of strings.\n- Each item in \"facts\" must be a single standalone memory string.\n- Do not return objects inside \"facts\".\n- Do not return classifications as JSON fields.\n- If needed, prefix each memory string with FACT:, OPINION:, or PROJECTION:.\n\nWhat to extract:\n- source-grounded facts, opinions, and projections that are useful for later analytical retrieval\n- named entities, organizations, products, markets, locations, dates, figures, percentages, prices, benchmarks, regulations, risks, causes, consequences, and comparisons\n- source metadata when explicitly available in the conversation, such as title, publisher, author, publication date, URL, and document type\n\nRules for each memory string:\n- make it understandable when retrieved alone\n- preserve exact names, dates, numbers, units, currencies, and percentages when available\n- preserve attribution when available\n- preserve causal links, comparisons, dependencies, and implications when available\n- keep memories atomic and specific\n- do not invent missing information\n- ignore filler, SEO text, navigation, cookie banners, calls to action, and repetitive boilerplate\n- do not extract conversation management text or generic assistant behavior\n\nExamples:\n{\"facts\": [\"FACT: According to Example News, published on 2025-08-12, the average annual home insurance premium for apartment tenants in Paris was 160 EUR.\", \"OPINION: Analyst Jane Doe argues that climate risk is increasing pressure on home insurance pricing in France.\", \"PROJECTION: The source expects further premium increases in 2026 due to recurring climate-related claims.\"]}\n\nConversation:\n{messages}"
}
